In this study, we prepared a novel graphene-like stacked carbon nanotube-supported Fe-Ni alloy nanometer composite material. The cubic structure of nickel dimethylglyoxime was synthesized as the base material. Under hydrothermal condition, FePc was adsorbed on the surface of the nickel dimethylglyoxime cube. In addition, hydrogen peroxide not only decomposes FePc into Pc and Fe2+, but also reduces Fe2+ to Fe. On the other hand, hydrogen peroxide was first found could decompose and peel the cube of nickel dimethylglyoxime into a novel type of nanotubes with graphene-like nanosheet stacking structure. After the final calcination, the Fe2+ and Ni2+ were converted to FeNi alloy, and the dimethylglyoxime carrier with its loaded Pc was converted to carbon material. The novel structure has a large BET, which is conducive to electron transport, product transport and provides a large active site for Fe-Ni3 alloy. The composite has high electro-catalysis performance for OER and ORR, which provides a new idea for the study of new energy reserves, energy conversion and reserve materials. This study provides a new idea for preparing novel carbon nanotube-loaded transition metal composites in the field of electrocatalysis. Image, graphical abstract Keywords Graphene-like Layered structure Carbon nanotubes Fe-Ni alloy Oxygen evolution reaction Oxygen reduction reaction 1 Introduction At present, the development of green energy is an important way to solve the current global energy crisis. The prospect of using transition metal catalysts for low-cost electrolysis of water to produce O2 has attracted much attention as a way to both mitigate global warming and generate green energy or green chemicals [1–6]. The electrochemical method of producing hydrogen and oxygen is expected to replace the traditional methods of high energy consumption and high pollution of fossil fuels. In the recent research on catalysts, low cost, simple synthesis procedure, high electro-catalytic activity and good stability are still the current research focus and development direction [7,8]. In principle, *OOH (*representative catalyst) desorption in the oxygen evolution reaction (OER) and oxygen reduction reaction (ORR) in electrocatalytic reactions is an important step in determining the reaction rate. The catalytic effect of Pt groups is well known, but the rarity and cost of precious metals are prohibitive, which prevents its development and application in electro-catalysis [9–13]. Therefore, it is necessary to design an efficient, low-cost and easy way to synthesize catalyst that does not contain precious metals. In current, carbon material is considered to be the predominant catalyst carrier because of its high specific surface area, good electrical conductivity and specific structure. Graphene [14–16], carbon nanotubes [17–19], carbon spheres [20–22], mesoporous carbon [23–25] and carbon nanofibers [26–28] are the focus of recent research. For example, both the three-dimensional carbon nanotube-doped FeNi alloy studied by Wang et al. [29] and the S-doped ordered mesoporous carbon designed by Jiang [30] showed excellent OER activity under alkaline conditions. Xhe [31], Chen [32], Khan [33] and et al. synthesized a variety of catalysts using graphene as the support and the material showed good activity in OER and ORR electro-catalysis. But in various morphologies of carbon materials, there are few reports on graphene-like nanosheet layered nanotube. In recent years, Ni based carbon has become the focus and direction of many researchers because of its high specific surface area, abundant pore structure and diversified composition. The ability of oxygen and hydrogen evolution can be enhanced by co-metal doping on nickel foam [34–37]. Mou [38], Li [39], Yang [40], Qiu [41] et al. have prepared bimetallic catalysts by growing transition metals on nickel foam. Due to the synergistic effect between bimetals and the special structure, the activity on HER/OER/ORR is very considerable. Numerous studies have shown that a large surface area in the catalyst increases the electron transfer rate [42–44], product transport [45,46], and gas diffusion [47,48]. The porous structure of the catalyst can enhance the transfer and adsorption of the reactants to get close to the active center and maximize the burst of the active site, resulting in a significant increase in catalytic activity [49,50]. For example, the defective MOF prepared by Ding and et al. [51] in the latest study contains more oxygen vacancies due to the porous structure, which significantly improves the catalytic activity. Because the porous structure contains more oxygen vacancies, more FeNi active sites are exposed. The metal active site plays a crucial role in catalyzing the first step of adsorption in the reaction. Compared with single metal foams, nickel and iron in nickel–iron foam show strong synergistic effect and enhanced electro-catalytic activity [52,53]. Moreover, the presence of iron plays an important role in improving the catalytic activity of OER/HER/ORR, such as increasing the inherent activity of the interface, providing more active sites, reducing the internal charge transfer resistance of the structure, and accelerating the reaction kinetic process [54]. In addition, double transition metal doping is considered to be a suitable candidate for electrocatalyst [55]. For example, the ferrocene-based bimetal CoFe-PBA designed by Zhang et al. [56] has achieved good catalytic activity in OER. Wang et al. [57] have designed the double-transition metal-doped NiFe-PBA layered nanoflower overcomes the low energy barrier and improves the OER reaction efficiency. The materials obtained from the above works have relatively high electrocatalytic performance. However, the preparation steps need to be further simplified, the experimental conditions need to be further optimized, and the electrocatalytic performance and stability need to be further improved. Based on the above materials, in this work, we adopted a simple, green and economical method to design and synthesize GF-CNT@Fex-Ni3 materials with graphene-like nanosheet stacking structure. In recent years, iron phthalocyanine has been studied as a potential cathode catalyst [58]. In this work, iron phthalocyanine is used as the Fe source. The cubic structure of nickel dimethylglyoxime was synthesized as the base material. Under hydrothermal condition, FePc was adsorbed on the surface of the cube. Then hydrogen peroxide was used as reducing agent and decomposing agent. Its function not only reduce the Fe2+ in FePc to Fe, but also decompose and peel the nickel dimethylglyoxime cube, and so that it finally has a novel graphene-like structure. After being calcined, a new structure with Fe-Ni alloy loaded on carbon nanotubes stacked with graphene-like nanosheets was synthesized for the first time. Moreover, the phthalein basket adsorbed on the surface of nickel dimethylglyoxime is converted into carbon and stacked carbon nanotubes combined with graphene-like nanosheets after high-temperature calcination. By combining the synergistic effect between graphene and transition metal, we design a simple synthesis route to prepare a relatively novel catalyst. The graphene-like layered stacked structure synthesized by this method has a large specific surface area, which cannot only play an accelerated role in electron transport, but also provide more active sites for product transport and transition metal alloys. As expected, the electro-catalytic performance for OER and ORR of the optimal GF-CNT@Fe-Ni3 was good with Tafel slopes of 64.6 mV dec−1 and 75.88 mV dec−1 respectively. In this work, the catalyst obtained good electrocatalytic activity under the combined action of nitrogen doping and FeNi3 alloys. Among them, FeNi3 alloy plays a very important role as the active site adsorbed OH− in OER for oxygen evolution reaction and adsorbed H2O molecules in ORR for oxygen reduction reaction [59]. The catalyst synthesized by this method can effectively reduce the energy barrier in OER and ORR reactions. Moreover, the overall reaction process of OER and ORR are accelerated due to the positive promotion of *OOH desorption by FeNi3 alloy. Therefore, it can be widely used in the field of fuel cells, metal air battery charging and water cracking. This study not only reduces the cost of synthesis of efficient catalysts, but also provides a valuable way for the preparation of novel non-noble metal oxygen electro-catalysts with excellent catalytic performance. This flexible preparation strategy also provides a broader prospect for the future development of binary metal alloy electro-catalysts. 2 Experimental section 2.1 Chemical reagents Nafion, dimethylglyoxime, iron phthalocyanine (FePc), Nickel chloride hexahydrate, acetone, hydrogen peroxide, sodium hydroxide, potassium hydroxide, ethanol (95 %) were purchased from Macklin Biochemical Co. One of the more striking is that the added hydrogen peroxide has a dual role. Hydrogen peroxide not only reduce FePc to Fe2+, but also adsorb Pc on the surface of nickel dimethylglyoxime as a C source. In addition, hydrogen peroxide also plays a role in the decomposition and stripping of nickel dimethylglyoxime, making it form a new type of graphene-like nanosheet stacked carbon nanotubes structure. Nickel dimethylglyoxime cube is composed of carbon skeleton and Ni2+. Hydrogen peroxide reduces Ni2+ to Ni while reducing Fe2+. Due to the reduction of most of the Ni2+, a large amount of Ni2+ is lost in the nickel dimethylglyoxime cube and a defective carbon skeleton is formed. Another reason is that due to the decomposition effect of hydrogen peroxide, the nickel cube of dimethylglyoxime is decomposed and stripped to form layered structure of nickel dimethylglyoxime. The rotation speed was fixed at 1600 rpm to allow for an efficient as-generated H2O2 diffusion to the Pt ring with minimized H2O2 decomposition. Fig. S9 shows the ORR polarization curves of catalysts with different dopants in RRDE in 0.1 M KOH, together with the H2O2 currents detected by the Pt ring. It is clear that the current on the ring is smaller than the current on the disk. As shown in the Fig. 5c, d the number of transferred electrons and the H2O2 yield of GF-CNT@Fe2-Ni3 (n ≈ 3.88, H2O2% ≈ 6.9 %) are close to the properties of commercial Pt materials. In contrast, the number of transferred electrons and H2O2 yield of GF-CNT@Fe2-Ni3 (n ≈ 3.33, H2O2% ≈ 40.1 %) and GF-CNT@Fe0.5-Ni3 (n ≈ 3.6, H2O2% ≈ 33.5 %) are far from those of material GF-CNT@Fe2-Ni3 [86–88]. In addition, reliable criteria for judging ORR activity are the starting potential (E onest) and half-wave potential (E 1/2) of electro catalysis. E onest is the potential when the current starts to rise. E 1/2 is the potential when the overall current density is half [89,90]. The RDE test results (Fig. S10) show that E onest and E 1/2 of GF-CNT@Fe2-Ni3 (0.79 V, 0.61 V) are bigger than GF-CNT@Fe2-Ni3 and GF-CNT@Fe0.5-Ni3 (0.79 V, 0.76 V). This further confirms that the 4e− pathway is the favorable route for the ORR process on surface of the GF-CNT@Fe2-Ni3 in 0.1 M KOH environment. As shown in Fig. 5g-a, a negligible decrease is observed for the current response of GF-CNT@Fe2-Ni3 whereas Pt/C exhibits a remarkable current decay under same condition (Fig. 5g-b), implying that GF-CNT@Fe2-Ni3 has a superior selectivity along with great methanol tolerance as compared to Pt/C. In addition, the CV reduction peak size and position of material GF-CNT@Fe2-Ni3 remained almost unchanged before and after methanol addition, but on the contrary, the CV curve of Pt/C smoothed after methanol addition and no reduction peak appeared. In addition, i-t was also carried out for the GF-CNT@Fe2-Ni3 to further probe its stability (Fig. S11). The GF-CNT@Fe2-Ni3 maintains 87 % of its initial current density after 30,000 s of continuous ORR at operating potential of 0.85 V. This is favorable evidence for the good durability and stability of the GF-CNT@Fe2-Ni3 towards ORR. 4 Conclusion In this study, a novel graphene-like nanosheet-stacked carbon nanotube structure with FeNi alloy has been synthesized for the first time. In conclusion, we have successfully constructed and optimized a Ni-MOF-based Fe atomic catalyst with different valent state inorganic complex through a new chemical route. For the first time, hydrogen peroxide was found not only to be reductive, but also has the function of decomposition and stripping. The cube of nickel dimethylglyoxime was decomposed and stripped into a new type of carbon nanotube structure stacked with graphene-like nanosheets by hydrogen peroxide. Finally, after being calcined, a new structure with Fe-Ni alloy loaded on carbon nanotubes stacked with graphene-like nanosheets was formed. Then GF-CNT@Fe2-Ni3 nanocomposite was confirmed to be the optimal catalyst for high-performance ORR and OER catalysis. In addition to low synthesis cost, green and easy access to raw GF-CNT@Fe2-Ni3, OER and ORR activities are also good and even comparable to commercial materials. Expectations for future applications of reagents are high. coredata.dc:description: In this study, we prepared a novel graphene-like stacked carbon nanotube-supported Fe-Ni alloy nanometer composite material. The cubic structure of nickel dimethylglyoxime was synthesized as the base material. Under hydrothermal condition, FePc was adsorbed on the surface of the nickel dimethylglyoxime cube. In addition, hydrogen peroxide not only decomposes FePc into Pc and Fe2+, but also reduces Fe2+ to Fe. On the other hand, hydrogen peroxide was first found could decompose and peel the cube of nickel dimethylglyoxime into a novel type of nanotubes with graphene-like nanosheet stacking structure. After the final calcination, the Fe2+ and Ni2+ were converted to FeNi alloy, and the dimethylglyoxime carrier with its loaded Pc was converted to carbon material. The novel structure has a large BET, which is conducive to electron transport, product transport and provides a large active site for Fe-Ni3 alloy. The composite has high electro-catalysis performance for OER and ORR, which provides a new idea for the study of new energy reserves, energy conversion and reserve materials. This study provides a new idea for preparing novel carbon nanotube-loaded transition metal composites in the field of electrocatalysis.
